In JavaScript, a simple method to find the common elements in two arrays is to use the `Array.prototype.reduce` function. In this case, the elements in the two arrays are nested into a single array using the `Array.prototype.concat` function, and then removed using the `Array.prototype.filter` function, which returns all elements of the result array that are common in both arrays. The result of the filtering process is returned as the output.

```javascript
// Use Array.prototype.reduce to nest the elements in the two arrays
const result = [...arr1, ...arr2].reduce((accumulator, currentValue) => {
  if (accumulator.includes(currentValue)) {
    return accumulator;
  } else {
    accumulator.push(currentValue);
    return accumulator;
  }
}, []);

// Use Array.prototype.filter to remove all elements from the result array that are common in both arrays
const filtered = result.filter((value) => {
  return arr1.includes(value) || arr2.includes(value);
});
```
This code example demonstrates the simple procedure for implementing a program to find the common elements in two arrays without using additional data structures. The `Array.prototype.reduce` function uses the concatenation of array objects to nest and make all elements from the two arrays comparable, while `Array.prototype.filter` removes all elements from the result array that are common in the two arrays.

